{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17518471","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17518471"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:05:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12926"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12926"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.11,0.04,0.01,0.17]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5364"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40561"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5364","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5364"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12926"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25337"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"2959"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9420"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9773"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10356"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40561","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40561"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old man is admitted to ICU following a myocardial infarction. He presents with profound hypotension secondary to low cardiac output, requiring inotropic and vasopressor support. His medical history includes hypertension (previously managed with amlodipine) and type 2 diabetes mellitus (previously managed with metformin). Both medications have been discontinued in ICU.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, the patient is anxious and clammy. His blood pressure is 90/60 mmHg, pulse is 110/min, respiratory rate is 22/min, and his temperature is 36.8\u00b0C. He weighs 70 kg. Chest examination reveals decreased breath sounds at the lung bases and the heart sounds are dual with no added sounds. Lower limb examination reveals bilateral pitting oedema. He has no rash. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOver the next 48 hours, his serum creatinine rises from 106 \u00b5mol/L to 310 \u00b5mol/L. His urine output is 20mL/hr. Urine dipstick demonstrates glycosuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute tubular necrosis","Acute interstitial nephritis","Contrast-induced nephropathy","IgA nephropathy","Diabetic nephropathy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical picture of this patient suggests \u003Cstrong\u003Eacute tubular necrosis (ATN)\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the most common cause of intrinsic acute kidney injury (AKI). Risk factors for ATN include hypotension, sepsis, and exposure to nephrotoxins. ATN typically manifests a few days after one of these risk factors and presents with a rapid increase in serum creatinine and decreased urine output (oliguria). \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute interstitial nephritis (AIN):\u003C/strong\u003E AIN is usually associated with medications, infections, or autoimmune diseases. Clinical signs may include fever, rash, and eosinophilia. Given the absence of these signs, this diagnosis is less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContrast-induced nephropathy (CIN):\u003C/strong\u003E CIN typically arises after the administration of iodinated contrast, often used in procedures like CT scans or angiographies. Although the patient is in ICU post-MI, there was no mention of him undergoing any procedure that required the administration of iodinated contrast. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgA nephropathy:\u003C/strong\u003E IgA nephropathy is a glomerular disease characterized by the deposition of IgA in the glomeruli. Patients may present with hematuria, which might be macroscopic (visible blood in urine) or microscopic. There is often a history of a preceding infection, especially respiratory or gastrointestinal. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDiabetic nephropathy:\u003C/strong\u003E This is a complication of long-standing diabetes mellitus and would manifest as proteinuria, especially albuminuria. The course of diabetic nephropathy is usually chronic rather than an acute rise in creatinine. \u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["ATN typically manifests a few days after a renal insult and presents as AKI with a rapid increase in serum creatinine and decreased urine output (oliguria). It is crucial to differentiate between ATN and other causes of AKI as the management may differ."],"references":["Basile DP, Anderson MD, Sutton TA. Pathophysiology of acute kidney injury. Compr Physiol. 2012 Apr;2(2):1303-53. doi: 10.1002/cphy.c110041. PMID: 23798302; PMCID: PMC3919808."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25337"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12926"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25337","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25337"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-24T16:35:29+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-11-24T16:35:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5364"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40561"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:52:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"